Git Commands for DevOps

These are some of the most commonly used Git commands during DevOps work. Every command below includes what it does and when we use it.

Git Definition

Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes in source code and collaborate with multiple developers.

Git History

Git was created by Linus Torvalds in 2005 for managing Linux kernel development. It is fast, distributed, and widely used in modern DevOps workflows.

Git Workflow

Working Directory → Staging Area → Repository

Working Directory
Where you create and modify files.

Staging Area
Where files are prepared before committing.

Repository
Where final changes are stored permanently.

Installation Command

yum install git -y
Installs Git on Linux system automatically without asking for confirmation.

Repository Initialization

git init
Initializes a new Git repository in current directory.

Adding Files

git add .
Adds all files to staging area.

git add file1
Adds a specific file.

git add file1 file2
Adds multiple files.

Checking Status

git status
Shows current status of files (modified, staged, untracked).

Commit Commands

git commit -m "message" file1
Commits a specific file with a message.

git commit -m "message" file1 file2
Commits multiple files.

git commit -m "message" .
Commits all staged files.

Viewing History

git log
Displays detailed commit history.

git log --oneline
Displays commits in short format.

git log --pretty=oneline
Displays each commit in a single line.

git log -2
Shows last 2 commits.

git log --follow --all
Tracks history across all branches and file changes.

git show commitid
Shows details of a specific commit.

git show commitid --stat
Shows commit details with file changes summary.

git show <commit-id>
Displays changes introduced in that commit.

Version Information

git --version
Displays installed Git version.

Configuration Commands

git config user.name "username"
Sets Git username.

git config user.email "emailid"
Sets Git email.

git config --list
Displays all Git configurations.

Removing Files

git rm --cached file1
Removes file from staging area but keeps it in working directory.

git rm file1
Removes file from both staging and working directory.

git rm --cached *.txt
Removes all .txt files from staging.

.gitignore File

.gitignore
Used to ignore files and folders from being tracked by Git.

Example:

*.log → ignores all log files
node_modules/ → ignores folder
*.env → ignores environment files

git add -f file1
Forces Git to add ignored files.

Amend Commands

git commit --amend -m "message"
Modifies last commit message.

git commit --amend --author="username <email>"
Changes author of last commit.

Amend Explanation

Amend is used to modify the most recent commit without creating a new commit.
Useful for fixing commit message or adding missed changes.

Branch Commands

git branch
Lists all branches.

git branch branchname
Creates a new branch.

git checkout branchname
Switches to another branch.

git checkout -b branchname
Creates and switches to a new branch.

git branch -d branchname
Deletes a branch.

Merge Commands

git merge branchname
Merges branch into current branch.

Remote Repository Commands

git remote add origin url
Adds remote repository.

git remote -v
Displays remote repositories.

git push origin main
Pushes code to remote repository.

git pull origin main
Fetches and merges changes from remote.

git clone url
Clones a repository.

Difference Commands

git diff
Shows differences between files.

git diff --staged
Shows staged changes.

Undo Commands

git restore file1
Restores file to last committed state.

git reset file1
Unstages file.

git reset --hard
Resets everything (use carefully).

Important Notes

Git tracks changes, not files
Always use meaningful commit messages
.gitignore helps avoid unnecessary files
Use amend only for last commit
Avoid force push in shared repositories
Check status before commit

